The London comparison has been a tough one for NBC, at least in the ratings=
 department. Even with the benefit of showing Usain Bolt live in prime time=
 for the first time, NBC=E2=80=99s Sunday night telecast earned a 14.9 rati=
ng and 26.7 million viewers, down from a 17.5 rating and 31.3 million viewe=
rs for the same night four years ago, and a 16.0 rating and 27.2 million fo=
r the Beijing Olympics eight years ago. In fact, it was the lowest rated mi=
ddle Sunday since 1984 (the addition of streaming and alternate channels im=
proved the numbers somewhat, but they were still less than either of the la=
st two Olympics); nearly every night of coverage has seen similar declines,=
 resulting in an average of 17% fewer viewers than four years ago.

As a like-to-like comparison, this year=E2=80=99s middle Sunday exceeded al=
l of those totals; from The Wrap ( https://www.thewrap.com/middle-sunday-ol=
ympics-viewership-nbc-peacock/ ) :

The middle Sunday of the 2024 Olympics drew in the second largest daily aud=
ience the Paris Games have seen to date. Sunday=E2=80=99s coverage =E2=80=
=94 which saw team U.S.A. score medals from Noah Lyles, Suni Lee and Bobby =
Finke =E2=80=94 brought in 35.4 million viewers, according to fast national=
 data from Nielsen and Adobe Analytics. Viewership for the second Sunday of=
 competition more than doubled the 17.4 million viewers that tuned in to th=
e comparable Sunday of competition during the Tokyo Olympics.

It=E2=80=99s dangerous to draw too many lessons from such a small sample si=
ze, but at the same time, it=E2=80=99s the small sample size that is kind o=
f the point: in a world defined by content abundance, which increasingly ma=
nifests itself in personally tailored experiences, the desire for a monocul=
tural experience seems to be both massive and accelerating.

Peacock=E2=80=99s Abundance
-------------------

From Brian Stelter at Wired ( https://www.wired.com/story/nbc-peacock-2024-=
summer-olympics-coverage/ ) :

I start every morning of the Summer Games the same way: by turning on the l=
iving room TV, saying the word =E2=80=9COlympics=E2=80=9D into a Comcast-po=
wered remote control, and clicking the Gold Zone icon. It=E2=80=99s like pu=
tting my TV set on autopilot. For the rest of the day Comcast=E2=80=99s NBC=
Universal is in charge, showing skateboarding or swimming one minute, fenci=
ng or field hockey the next=E2=80=94and sometimes 10 sports in 10 boxes sim=
ultaneously. I call my kids over to the TV when Team USA is about to win a =
medal. I mute it for long stretches of the day. It=E2=80=99s like having a =
live portal to Paris, or at least a very sophisticated screensaver.

You may experience the Olympics in a totally different fashion. Maybe you s=
wipe through videoclips on TikTok. Maybe you stream the raw feeds of your f=
avorite obscure sport on Peacock. Maybe you watch NBC=E2=80=99s whiz-bang p=
rime time recap. Maybe you tune into some highlight show I haven=E2=80=99t =
even discovered yet. Ultimately, we=E2=80=99re all still watching the same =
global spectacle, albeit from different angles and with different narrators=
.

It=E2=80=99s a rare instance of fragmentation being to streaming=E2=80=99s =
benefit; the Olympics illustrate how all the shattered pieces can be stuck =
back together. =E2=80=9CThese days, it=E2=80=99s not often that we can unit=
e people and bring them together around something,=E2=80=9D says Molly Solo=
mon, executive producer and president of NBC Olympics Production. =E2=80=9C=
The Olympics is doing it.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=A6

NBC=E2=80=99s have-it-your-way approach was borne out of technological nece=
ssity. Millions of viewers still like to wake up to the Today show=E2=80=99=
s teary-eyed interviews with gold medalists and fall asleep to the prime ti=
me team=E2=80=99s heartfelt come-from-behind stories. But that traditional =
production=E2=80=94gauzy, promotional, and packed with commercials=E2=80=94=
doesn=E2=80=99t appeal to everyone, particularly in an age of instantaneous=
 push alerts and social media memes about the games. So for the first time,=
 NBCUniversal decided to stop gatekeeping the hottest events of the day unt=
il US prime time. Biles=E2=80=99 gold medal feats have been shown live duri=
ng the day and again at night. =E2=80=9CNo holding back=E2=80=9D is how Sol=
omon describes it. =E2=80=9CWe are here for the audience.=E2=80=9D

This is the other reason why I think the Olympics have been a hit: NBC abso=
lutely nailed the presentation across all of its platforms. Start with an i=
mportant caveat: Europe is a pretty good time zone for linear TV. Events co=
uld be televised live across NBC=E2=80=99s family of channels during the da=
y, and then in the evening NBC showed =E2=80=9CPrimetime in Paris=E2=80=9D,=
 a three-hour special that presented the day=E2=80=99s most popular competi=
tions as if they were live, along with highlights, interviews of winners, e=
tc. I thought these primetime specials were excellent, and were how I consu=
med most of the Olympics, often going out of my way to avoid spoilers.

What NBC did not do is take that choice out of my hands: as Stelter noted, =
NBC gave up on gate-keeping events like the gymnastics finals, instead show=
ing them twice, both live and in primetime. All of this was augmented by Pe=
acock: while NBC has a lot of channels, they can=E2=80=99t show everything,=
 but nearly everything was on Peacock, both live and on-demand. Moreover, a=
s Stelter notes, Peacock offered non-traditional ways of viewing, including=
 Gold Zone and multiview.

What this entire effort represented was a shift in mindset away from a worl=
d of scarcity to a world of abundance; it reminds me of how Spotify transfo=
rmed the music industry; from a 2022 Update ( https://stratechery.com/2022/=
spotify-audiobooks-audiobook-business-models-limitations-and-skepticism/?ac=
cess_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubG=
luZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJh=
enAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF=
0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIyL3Nwb3RpZnktYXVkaW9ib29rcy1hdWRpb2Jvb2stYnVzaW5lc3MtbW=
9kZWxzLWxpbWl0YXRpb25zLWFuZC1za2VwdGljaXNtLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzI2MDUyNjYwLCJpY=
XQiOjE3MjM0NjA2NjAsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIs=
InNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQ=
gZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2=
VzcyJ9.Poyo8ykX3P0ztdy5bfkpJ6PBb9ZPA25AvGnhGUGpfcClInXnXM_4_GxmHApW7tbYNHho=
E5jTMY0lBNg-LFKT7nZpxnnK1YOMyHYiw5u-p5WVmY7xjFQGYyZ9GTZq4qaN5s20Q2Cavi1F0DZ=
OzBC-Q_0FWzNKX9ITQ1lmWBn82WeQFALmx3DnK1gv1vF7Nn5zFeBxP0CFI3juQIh4VguqfboDzp=
Hi0PDDG6Sajp0xTKK1Q6GtHeZsOm5CF4FjQF9SFaIL0VsqTgCgrp1VDAULXuj2wcGng6EnKIaXg=
qPQII3MF-xLT4di0Im67ljmp9xvJGn90gN0vC4w-ld_MKyQnA ) :

What made the company so transformational is that the all-you-can-eat subsc=
ription model dragged the music industry towards a business model that didn=
=E2=80=99t fight the Internet but was rather enabled by it. While the analo=
g world was about scarcity (because additional goods have marginal costs), =
the Internet is about abundance (because additional digital goods don=E2=80=
=99t): what Spotify did was leverage that reality and make it super conveni=
ent to access; to put it another way, Spotify didn=E2=80=99t sell music, it=
 sold convenience, and the music industry has been raking it in ever since:

Music industry revenue over time ( https://www.riaa.com/u-s-sales-database/=
 )

In the case of the Olympics, NBC has long paid the IOC for broadcasting rig=
hts; in a world of scarcity the way to monetize those rights was through ex=
clusive broadcasting windows. This is how you ended up with tape-delayed br=
oadcasts of high profile events like the 100m dash, and a complete inabilit=
y to watch anything that wasn=E2=80=99t high profile enough to fit on a lin=
ear TV schedule. In the Internet-defined world of abundance, however, the b=
etter solution is to sell convenience and choice, and Peacock did a great j=
ob of exactly that.

Comcast Earnings
----------------

Last month, from the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage=
/stock-market-today-earnings-dow-sp500-nasdaq-07-23-2024/card/comcast-reven=
ue-weighed-down-by-theme-parks-movie-business-9OTW1mETrCBSDM7xpX0B ) :

Comcast=E2=80=99s revenue dipped in the second quarter, as declines in the =
theme park and movie businesses more than offset growth in areas like wirel=
ess service and broadband. The cable and entertainment giant said revenue f=
ell 2.7% overall to $29.7 billion and net profit decreased 7.5% to $3.9 bil=
lion. The company posted adjusted earnings per share of $1.21, up from $1.1=
3 in the year-earlier quarter and above analyst estimates. Shares of Comcas=
t fell around 6% in morning trading=E2=80=A6

Subscribers to the Peacock streaming service dropped to 33 million from 34 =
million in the second quarter, in which the lineup of fresh sports and ente=
rtainment content tends to be weaker. Executives said a new, 11-year media-=
rights deal the company=E2=80=99s NBCUniversal unit struck with the NBA, wh=
ich will cost some $2.5 billion per year starting with the 2025-2026 season=
, will help smooth out the calendar. =E2=80=9COpportunities like this come =
along very rarely,=E2=80=9D said Comcast CEO Brian Roberts. Peacock narrowe=
d its adjusted operating loss to $348 million from $639 million in the prev=
ious quarter, as Comcast and many of its rivals push to make streaming prof=
itable.

Here is the rub in terms of the glowing Peacock review: I assume that Peaco=
ck=E2=80=99s subscriber numbers will improve a lot this quarter; losses wil=
l probably also increase, as the cost of those Olympics rights hit the book=
s. And then, of course, Comcast has to figure out how to retain those new s=
ign-ups: a one-month subscription to Peacock was the best deal in entertain=
ment for the past two weeks; the ease of cancellation makes it even better.

The NBA deal does help: starting in 2026 Comcast=E2=80=99s second quarters =
will include the NBA playoffs, which will be a reason to subscribe =E2=80=
=94 or stay subscribed, particularly after football. In both cases, though,=
 Comcast is paying a lot of money to acquire and retain customers for a ser=
vice that loses a lot of money. There is the old axiom that the easiest way=
 to drive revenue is to sell $1 for $0.90; is the easiest way to provide a =
great streaming experience to lose hundreds of millions of dollars a quarte=
r, and cannibalize the linear TV business that was the foundation of not ju=
st your network but also your infrastructure business?

That last bit is why I have long been more mystified by Peacock than any of=
 the other streaming services: it=E2=80=99s not just that moving content to=
 Peacock degrades the value of NBC Universal=E2=80=99s cable channels; it a=
lso degrades the value of the bundle as a whole, which Comcast is built on.=
 However, Comcast=E2=80=99s decisions with Peacock are perhaps better under=
stood in the light of the Charter-Disney stand-off last fall; from The Rise=
 and Fall of ESPN=E2=80=99s Leverage ( https://stratechery.com/2023/the-ris=
e-and-fall-of-espns-leverage/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6In=
N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVj=
aGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW5=
0Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL3RoZS1yaXNlLWFuZC1mYW=
xsLW9mLWVzcG5zLWxldmVyYWdlLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNzI2MDUyNjYwLCJpYXQiOjE3MjM0NjA2N=
jAsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVl=
ZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnR=
zIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.P6CwHcFIm=
2tObNdabnXVSXhuSoEIzuT2JFhzCIEjLW6MNbquKOYYax7Cr6Ehh9Hzwgh4mbtvboKRe3OUmTku=
