to-3Hy7I4hVPray6xJ6-2ZyUQqvp1jjKcRbljT0MQAikNMeAlcZmApuoKnkcKrHMF2cl37fTm3S=
UADQW0DYJNBO0b6wWccvVUl3uM9tZvC-Q ) :

When Disney went dark on Charter last week, I initially assumed a similar o=
utcome; then came the Charter investor call the next morning, and this slid=
e ( https://ir.charter.com/static-files/05f899dd-7ef3-40d8-84c1-f16a7acfe31=
8 ) :

Charter's investor slide about video ( https://ir.charter.com/static-files/=
05f899dd-7ef3-40d8-84c1-f16a7acfe318 )

The most important sentence is in the light blue box on the far right: =E2=
=80=9CThe video product is no longer a key driver of financial performance.=
=E2=80=9D This is the culmination of a 25-year shift in business model for =
the cable companies: those initial investments in wires in the ground to pr=
ovide small communities access to big city TV broadcasts turned out to be v=
ery well suited to providing broadband Internet access. Remember the lesson=
 of RCA and ESPN=E2=80=99s founding: the digital transmission of informatio=
n is inherently indifferent to the data being distributed. In the case of c=
able the initial use case was digital TV signals, but the exact same cable =
could also carry packets running the TCP/IP protocol.

Of course for a long time it was very profitable to carry both, along with =
voice: cable companies offered =E2=80=9Ctriple play=E2=80=9D bundles that i=
ncluded TV, Internet, and telephony. Over time the telephony part dropped o=
ff, as people used mobile phones exclusively; cable carriers have since mov=
ed into the mobile carrier space as well, fueled by profits from TV and bro=
adband Internet. What made the Internet part the most valuable, though, is =
that the cable companies didn=E2=80=99t need to pay for content: everything=
 was just a packet.

This was in stark contrast to TV content, which was becoming increasingly e=
xpensive even as Internet-alternatives =E2=80=94 both specifically, in the =
case of vMVPDs like YouTube TV, and generally, in the case of content abund=
ance =E2=80=94 raised the value of broadband and diminished the profits of =
cable TV. These realities made TV a take-it-or-leave-it proposition for Cha=
rter; the case for Peacock is that Comcast made the same determination, but=
 instead of fighting with Disney they just unilaterally started to destroy =
the bundle themselves, to better position themselves for the future.

It=E2=80=99s not clear, of course, that that future will ever prove to be w=
orth the acceleration in the bundle=E2=80=99s demise, which again, hurt Com=
cast on two fronts (NBC Universal and cable TV sales); it is notable, thoug=
h, that Comcast=E2=80=99s core broadband business still makes a lot of mone=
y, which means Peacock has time that competitors like Max do not. Said time=
 will tell if this actually manifests into profits; at least we=E2=80=99re =
getting a great consumer experience in the meantime.

